gust 1212 to 7 October 1212","1280":"1280","about 1252":"about 1252","Italy":"Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"di","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 狄, a term referring to the tribes in ancient northern China: (i) from Di (狄), the name of an ancient state (thought to have been located in Hebei or Shandong province), which was granted to Xiao Bo or Kao Bo by King Cheng of Zhou (reigned 1042–1021  BC ). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Ku Di (庫狄) family during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) traced back to other minority ethnic groups in ancient northwestern China.","Mandarin form of the Chinese surname 邸, meaning ‘official residence’ in Chinese: (i) from placename Di (邸), the name of a county (unidentified location). (ii) said to be borne by some descendants of Kujula Kadphises (called 丘就郤 or 邸就郤 in Chinese, 30–<i>c.</i> 80  AD ), founder of the Kushan Empire (one branch of the Yuezhi people originating from western China) located in Central Asia during the Eastern Han dynasty (25–220  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Chi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Dong, Yun, Cheng, Jae, Yong, Cheng Chung, Chi, Chun, Duk, Fang, Feng.  Korean Chung, Chong, Jae Hong, Moon, Myong, Pong, Shen, Yoo, Byung, Chang, Chol, Chong Hun.  Southeast Asian Phi, Hung, Ly, Tu, Denh, Do Van, Duong, Hao, Kieu, Mui, Nga, Phat.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 池, meaning ‘moat’ in ancient Chinese: (i) acquired as a surname by people who lived beside a moat. (ii) from Chi (池), said to be the name of an ancient state (of unknown location and period). (iii) from the personal name Chi (池), personal name of a son of an official in the state of Qin during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 遲, meaning ‘late’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of Chi Ren (遲任), a person who lived during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) shortened form of the Chinese compound surname Yu-Chi (尉遲), originally the name of a tribe from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iii) from the second element of the personal name Zi Chi (子遲), style name of Fan Xu, a student of Confucius (551–479  BC )."]}]},{"name":"Celano","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Fiore, Guido, Osvaldo, Tullio, Vito, Antonio, Bernardo, Geno, Giuseppe, Leonardo, Marino, Mario, Nino, Orazio.","Italian: habitational name from a place called Celano, in L'Aquila province."],"variants":[{"name":"Celani","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Domenic, Dario, Gabriele, Matteo, Natale, Salvatore, Vincenzo.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Celano  ."]}]},{"name":"Tomaso","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament.  See  <b>Thomas</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thomas","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Comte Tomaso di Celano was born in 1182, in Italy, his father, Pietro di Celano, was 24 and his mother, Miss di Palearia, was 28. He had at least 1 son with Contessa Iodetta di Molise. He died about 1252, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1182–about 1252":"1182–umbes 1252","1182–1252":"1182–1252","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1159–1212":"1159–1212","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1215":"1215","1159":"1159","1212":"1212","1155":"1155","1252":"1252","ABT 1215"